<DOC><DOCNO> AP891018-0016 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-18-89 0006EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethruu a0769 10-18 0508</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethruu, a0769,0516</SECOND><HEAD>Flooding In Appalachia, Temperatures Dropping</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: LEADS with eight grafs to UPDATE with Tug Fork cresting, 150evacuated; evacuations in four Kentucky counties; picks up 7th graf pvs,`Rain, showers ...'</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Heavy rain from the remnants of Hurricane Jerry triggeredflooding in the Appalachians Tuesday, closing roads and schools andforcing evacuations in West Virginia and Kentucky. Rain fell acrossmuch of the rest of the East.   Up to 4 inches of rain fell on southern West Virginia. Schoolswere closed in four counties because rising water threatened toblock school buses.   Flooding on the Tug Fork of the Big Sandy River, along the WestVirginia-Kentucky line, would be the first test of the WestWilliamson floodwall, which was dedicated just this summer. Afloodwall protecting downtown Williamson is less than 60 percentcomplete.   The Tug Fork rose 3 feet an hour Tuesday afternoon. The rivercrested 6 feet above its banks at Matewan early in the evening andwas expected to crest 3 feet above flood stage at Williamsonovernight, the National Weather Service reported.   Floodwaters swept away an unoccupied house along the river inBoone County, officials said.   People from low-lying rural areas near Matewan and in Williamsonwere asked to leave their homes, officials said. About 150 peoplewere evacuated.   In southeastern Kentucky, where 4 to 6 inches of rain fell inthe 18 hours ended at 1 p.m. Tuesday, many roads were flooded orblocked by mudslides, the weather service said. Fast-rising creeksforced evacuations in Pike, Floyd, Clay and Jackson counties.   More than 760 students and faculty at McDowell Elementary andHigh School saw Frasure and Left Beaver creeks spill over theirbanks and flood school buildings with up to 3 feet of water earlyTuesday.   Rain, showers and occasional thunderstorms during the afternoonextended over much of New England, New York state, northern andeastern Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Maryland, much of Virginia, WestVirginia, Ohio, Kentucky, southern Indiana and southern Illinois.   Showers and thunderstorms also reached from western Georgiaacross the Florida Panhandle, Alabama, southern Mississippi,southeastern Louisiana and along the lower Texas Gulf Coast.   Scattered snow showers fell from north-central Wyoming tosouth-central Colorado, but no measurable amounts were reportedduring the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT. At dawn there was an inch ofsnow on the ground in Denver; Cheyenne, Wyo., and Limon, Colo.   Freeze warnings through Wednesday morning were posted forsections of Colorado, Kansas, Missouri, and Oklahoma. Overnightlows near freezing were expected in the Texas Panhandle andnortheastern New Mexico.   By contrast, a record high temperature for the date was set inCape Hatteras, N.C., where it was 83 degrees. Records were also setin Orlando, Fla., where it was 93 and Jacksonville, Fla., where itwas 91.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 32degrees at Custer, S.D., to 98 at Palm Springs, Calif. Tuesday'slow for the Lower 48 states was 11 in West Yellowstone, Mont.</TEXT></DOC>